1223":"1177–1223","1181–Female":"1181–Overleden","1202":"1202","1267":"1267","1223":"1223","1266":"1266","1177":"1177","about 1203":"circa 1203","1240":"1240","after 1223":"na 1223","1181":"1181","1207":"1207","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Buckton, Yorkshire, England":"Buckton, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Buckton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Buckton, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1202–1266":"1202–1266","1207–Male":"1207–Deceased","1223–1267":"1223–1267","1240–Male":"1240–Deceased","1177–1223":"1177–1223","1181–Female":"1181–Deceased","1202":"1202","1267":"1267","1223":"1223","1266":"1266","1177":"1177","about 1203":"about 1203","1240":"1240","after 1223":"after 1223","1181":"1181","1207":"1207","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Buckton, Yorkshire, England":"Buckton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Buckton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Buckton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Forrester","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>forester</i> ‘officer in charge of a forest or lord's hunting ground’ (Old French <i>forestier</i>, Anglo-Norman <i>forester</i>). See   Forrest  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Forister","meanings":["English: variant of   Forrester  ."]},{"name":"Forrest","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived in or near a royal forest, or a metonymic occupational name for a keeper or worker in one. Middle English <i>forest</i> was not, as today, a near-synonym of <i>wood</i>, but referred specifically to a large area of woodland reserved by law for the purposes of hunting by the king and his nobles. The same applied to the European cognates, both ancient Germanic and Romance. The English word is from Middle English <i>forest</i> ‘forest’, Old French <i>forest</i>, Late Latin <i>forestis (silva)</i>. This is generally taken to be a derivative of <i>foris</i> ‘outside’; the reference was probably to woods lying outside a settlement. On the other hand, Middle High German <i>for(e)st</i> has been held to be a derivative of Old High German <i>foraha</i> ‘fir’ (see   Forster  ), with the addition of a collective suffix.","Irish: this name is also frequently attested in Ireland, where it may be a variant of   Forrestal  ."]},{"name":"Forester","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Forrester   (see   Forrest  )."]},{"name":"Forrister","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Forrester  ."]},{"name":"Forster","meanings":["English: shortened form of   Forrester  , an occupational name for someone who worked in a forest.","English: possibly a Norman French nickname or occupational name from Old French <i>forcetier</i> ‘maker of scissors or shears, cutler’. Compare   Force   and   Forse  .","German (mainly <b>Förster</b>): agent derivative of Middle High German <i>forst</i> ‘forest’, denoting someone who lived in or near a royal forest, or who worked in one (see   Forst  ). This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine). Compare   Foerster  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Forrester was born in 1202, in Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Adam Forester of Etherstone, was 26 and his mother, Hawise, was 22. He had at least 1 son with Elizabeth Comyn. He died in 1266, at the age of 64."},"et":{"1202–1266":"1202–1266","1207–Male":"1207–Surnud","1223–1267":"1223–1267","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1177–1223":"1177–1223","1181–Female":"1181–Surnud","1202":"1202","1267":"1267","1223":"1223","1266":"1266","1177":"1177","about 1203":"umbes 1203","1240":"1240","after 1223":"pärast 1223","1181":"1181","1207":"1207","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Buckton, Yorkshire, England":"Buckton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Buckton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Buckton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1202–1266":"1202–1266","1207–Male":"1207–Kuollut","1223–1267":"1223–1267","1240–Male":"1240–Kuollut","1177–1223":"1177–1223","1181–Female":"1181–Kuollut","1202":"1202","1267":"1267","1223":"1223","1266":"1266","1177":"1177","about 1203":"noin 1203","1240":"1240","after 1223":"1223 jälkeen","1181":"1181","1207":"1207","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Buckton, Yorkshire, England":"Buckton, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Buckton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Buckton, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1202–1266":"1202–1266","1207–Male":"1207–Décédé","1223–1267":"1223–1267","1240–Male":"1240–Décédé","1177–1223":"1177–1223","1181–Female":"1181–Décédée","1202":"1202","1267":"1267","1223":"1223","1266":"1266","1177":"1177","about 1203":"environ 1203","1240":"1240","after 1223":"après 1223","1181":"1181","1207":"1207","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Écosse, Royaume-Uni","Buckton, Yorkshire, England":"Buckton, Everwyck, Ang